# Observability Standards

Never use print() or console.log() in application code.

Backend — use structlog:
import structlog
logger = structlog.get_logger(__name__)

logger.info("user.created", user_id=user.id, email=user.email)
logger.error("payment.failed", user_id=user.id, error=str(e), provider="stripe")

Frontend — use the shared logger utility:
import { logger } from '@/shared/utils/logger'
logger.info('auth.login_success', { userId })
logger.error('api.request_failed', { endpoint, statusCode })

What must be logged:
- All unhandled exceptions with stack trace
- All external API calls: service name, endpoint, duration, status
- All critical business events: user created, payment processed, etc.
- All auth events: login, logout, failed attempts, token refresh

What must never be logged:
- Passwords, tokens, or API keys
- PII beyond operational necessity
- Raw request bodies that may contain sensitive data

Log levels:
DEBUG   → local dev only, never production
INFO    → normal business events
WARNING → recoverable issues, degraded state
ERROR   → failures requiring attention
CRITICAL → system-level failures, immediate action required
